<article class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-white">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-5">
    <div class="prose max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">Having a good product or service is no longer enough. Today, before people call, visit, or request a quote, they check your online presence. They search your name, compare photos, read reviews, look at your social media, and decide whether your business feels trustworthy.</p>

      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-10">The good news is that you do not need to do everything at once. You need to build a clear, professional, and consistent foundation. These are the elements that matter most for a local business.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">1. A complete and active Google Business Profile</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">For a local business, Google Business Profile is one of the most important tools you have. It is what appears on Google Maps and in local search results when someone looks for services near them.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">An incomplete profile can cost you customers even if your business is better than the competition. At minimum, your profile should include:</p>
      <ul class="checklist mb-10">
        <li>Accurate name, phone number, address, and hours.</li>
        <li>The right business categories.</li>
        <li>Real, professional photos of your work, location, team, or products.</li>
        <li>A clear description of what you do and who you help.</li>
        <li>Recent reviews and thoughtful replies to customers.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">2. A website that explains and converts</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">Your website does not need to be complicated, but it does need to answer the questions a customer has before contacting you: what you do, where you work, why they should trust you, and how to get help.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-10">An effective site should load quickly on mobile, have clear call or WhatsApp buttons, show your services, and include trust signals like real photos, testimonials, service areas, and visible contact information.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">3. A consistent visual identity</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">Online presence is not only about showing up. It is also about looking professional. If your logo, colors, photos, posts, and printed materials look different everywhere, customers may feel that the business is not organized.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-10">A consistent identity helps people recognize and remember you. You do not need a massive brand system, but you do need a foundation: a clean logo, defined colors, readable typography, and materials that feel like they belong to the same business.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">4. Content that shows your business is active</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">When someone visits your social media and sees that the last post was months ago, they may assume the business is closed or neglected. Posting consistently helps keep your brand present.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">Not every post has to be perfect. What matters is that it is useful and real. You can post:</p>
      <ul class="checklist mb-10">
        <li>Before and after examples of completed work.</li>
        <li>Frequently asked customer questions.</li>
        <li>Promotions or featured services.</li>
        <li>Photos of your team, process, or products.</li>
        <li>Simple tips related to your industry.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">5. Reviews and social proof</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">Reviews are one of the strongest ways to build trust. A customer may not know you yet, but if they see that other people had a good experience, they are more likely to contact you.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-10">Ask for reviews after every successful job, respond professionally, and use positive comments on your website or social media. Social proof turns the trust of your current customers into a tool for attracting new ones.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">6. Digital advertising with a clear goal</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">Meta Ads and Google Ads can help a lot, but they work best when there is a strategy. Before you spend money, define what you want: calls, WhatsApp messages, website visits, bookings, or quote requests.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-10">You also need to send people somewhere prepared to convert, like a clear landing page or optimized Google profile. Otherwise, you may pay for clicks that never become customers.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">7. Basic tracking so you know what works</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-5">You do not need complicated reports to start. But you should know which channels generate calls, messages, or visits. Each month, review:</p>
      <ul class="checklist mb-10">
        <li>How many people viewed your Google profile.</li>
        <li>How many calls or clicks you received.</li>
        <li>Which posts had the most engagement.</li>
        <li>Which ads generated real contacts.</li>
        <li>Which website pages received the most visits.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="rounded-3xl p-8 sm:p-10 my-12" style="background:var(--primary-lt)">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-3" style="color:var(--primary)">Quick summary</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl mb-4" style="color:var(--primary-dk)">Online presence is built with clarity, trust, and consistency.</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-0">Start with Google Business Profile, a clear website, professional branding, consistent content, reviews, and well-targeted advertising. It is not about being everywhere. It is about showing up well in the places where your customers are already searching.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl mb-4">Where should your business start?</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you do not know which part of your online presence needs the most attention, start with a simple review: search your business on Google, open your website on a phone, look at your latest posts, and ask whether everything builds trust. If the answer is not clear, that is an opportunity to improve.</p>
